The movie "The Matrix" (1999) directed by The Wachowskis was the first-ever movie released in a twin format, with an additional 19 seconds of footage exclusive to theaters showing the film natively in IMAX.  The full story is included in the IMAX version, but it was taken out for standard theaters. The additional footage includes the scene where Neo (played by Keanu Reeves) is shown to ride his motorcycle at high speeds along the highway in the city, and later around the Matrix cityscape at high speeds. 
The additional footage removed from the standard version includes several nighttime scenes of "Zion", the underground city of humanity, where Morpheus (played by Laurence Fishburne), Trinity (played by Carrie-Anne Moss), and the rest of the crew gather around a large holographic interface to discuss the plan to send Neo on a mission to unplug a human battery in the Matrix. The extra footage where Neo rides his motorcycle can be seen in the cutoff on the DVD release, but it's not included in the IMAX version. The scenes were cut before the entire movie footage.

